<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-07-19T11:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-07-19T11:00:00-05:00" n="533" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d533">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 European War 1939/13299:
                            Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Egypt</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Kirk</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the
                                    <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Cairo</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-07-19T19:00:00+03:00">July 19,
                                    1941—7 p.m.</date>
                                <lb/> [Received July 20—3:27 p.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>981. My June 7, 3 p.m. With reference to an item released by Reuter
                            yesterday regarding renewed negotiations for the evacuation of French
                            women and children from French Somaliland, the Legation learns from a
                            British Embassy source that negotiations along these lines are taking
                            place. Furthermore it is stated that the situation in Djibouti has shown
                            marked signs of deterioration recently and that an early collapse would
                            not be surprising. British hopes in this respect are somewhat offset,
                            however, by the fear that, before finally giving in, the French
                            authorities will blow up the harbor and railway facilities at
                            Djibouti.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Kirk</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>